Facebook's Prophet Library

Facebook's Prophet Forecasting library is specifically designed to forecast the business data sets that are common at Facebook. Typically, daily or minute data sets are large data sets.

Note that this library is not meant to be better than ARIMA. However, it is an alternative.

The Prophet procedure is an additive regression model with four main components:

  • A piecewise linear or logistic growth curve trend. It automatically detects changes in trend by selecting change points from the data.
  • A yearly seasonal component modeled using a Fourier series.
  • A weekly seasonal component using dummy variables.
  • A user-provided list of important holidays.

Advantage: Prophet requires a few lines of code to produce forecasts along with upper and lower bounds.

Prophet is a very powerful tool. However, it is more like a black box, as we do not get to see all the information of the model, as we do not in ARIMA.

Prophet also includes its own diagnostic functionality. It allow us to perform cross-validation.

In the previous example we only check the model based on last part of the data. Howeve, with cross-validation we can evaluate the model with several sections of the data.

In[37]:
from prophet.diagnostics import cross_validation, performance_metrics
from prophet.plot import plot_cross_validation_metric

Here, we need to define three different components:

  • Initial training period
  • The period length we perform cross-validation
  • Horizon of prediction in each fold
In[38]:
### Initial training period (5 years)

### Prophet expects in days
initial = 5 * 365
initial = str(initial) + ' days'
initial
Out[38]:
'1825 days'
In[39]:
### Period (fold every 5 years)

period = 5 * 365
period = str(period) + ' days'
period
Out[39]:

In[40]:
### Horizon (1 year ahead)

horizon = 365
horizon = str(horizon) + ' days'
horizon
Out[40]:
'365 days'

df_cv = cross_validation(model = m, initial=initial, period = period, horizon=horizon)

In[56]:
### Let's check components

fig = m.plot_components(forecasts);

### If we carefully investigate, we can see that seasonality grows with trend. Thus, it is multiplicative.
### However, our forecasts do not capture this.
In[57]:
fig = m.plot(forecasts)
a = add_changepoints_to_plot(fig.gca(), m, forecasts);
In[58]:
### Now let's change seasonality to multiplicative

m = Prophet(seasonality_mode='multiplicative')
m.fit(df)
future = m.make_future_dataframe(periods=50, freq='MS')
forecasts = m.predict(future)
fig = m.plot(forecasts)

### Here we can see, forecasts capture the increase in trend and seasonality.
### We can also use train and test data to verify improvements.
